    {
      "id": "80fca0053f4dd5b86fdce78bdbb41df428e0fa9d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 126,
        "name": "Ned Bass",
        "email": "bass6@llnl.gov",
        "username": "nedbass"
      },
      "date": "2014-09-18 22:43:43.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 7:\n\nWe shouldn't validate layouts, we should provide interfaces that let users build valid layouts.  A bunch of functions to validate various aspects of an already-built layout will create a messy and awkward interface.  How would an application use such an API in practice?  Would it do a parameter search on each attribute, building layouts with various values until it finds a layout that passes validation? That is backwards.  A sane application would query the API to discover valid striping attribute values then build a layout using them. So lets design an interface that sane applications can use.\n        \nInstead of answering the question \"does this layout have a valid OST index?\", let's answer \"what OST indices are available?\"\n  \n\"What pools are available?\", not \"Does this layout have a valid pool?\"          \n\netc.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
